Introduction

CIC-DUX4 Sarcoma (CDS) is a high-grade sarcoma associated with high rates of metastasis, chemoresistance, and poor outcomes. This project utilizes RNA sequencing data to compare CDS to other types of sarcoma through the use of heat maps, PCA plots and targeted expression analysis. Here my analysis compares CDS cell lines to non-CDS cell lines by:

1. Reorgainizing data 
2. Using DESeq2 to define top varibaly expressed genes 
3. Generating PCA plots 
4. Visualizing exrpression of SHC3 and SHC4 in CDS and non-CDS cell lines

From this analysis, I was able to define SHC3 and SHC4 as two genes uniquely over expressed in CDS cells. Additionally, this analysis shows human CDS cell lines cluster together and away from other types of sarcoma cell lines, providing further evidence that CDS is distinct from other sarcoma sub-types.

generate_DE_results <- function(dds, comparisons, padjcutoff = 0.001)
# extract DESeq results between comparisons indicated
{
res <- results(dds, contrast = c("condition", comparisons[1],comparisons[2]))[,-c(3,4)]
# annotate the data with gene name
res <- as_tibble(res, rownames = "ensembl_id")
my_annoation <- read.csv("GRCh38.p13_annotation.csv", header = TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
res <- left_join(res, my_annoation, by = c("ensembl_id" = "Gene.stable.ID"))
# combine normalized counts with entire DE lsit 
normalized_counts <- round(counts(dds, normalized = TRUE),3)
combined_data <- as_tibble(cbind(res, normalized_counts))
combined_data <- combined_data[order(combined_data$log2FoldChange, decreasing= TRUE),]
#generate sorted lists with the indicated cutoff values
res <- res[order(res$log2FoldChange, decreasing = TRUE),]
           de_genes_padj <- res[which(res$padj < padjcutoff), 1]
# write output to files
write.csv (de_genes_padj, file = paste0(comparisons[1], "_vs_", comparisons[2], "_padj_cutoff.csv"), row.names = FALSE)
write.csv (combined_data, file = paste0(comparisons[1], "_vs_", comparisons[2], "_allgenes.csv"), row.names = FALSE)
  
  writeLines( paste0("For the comparison: ", comparisons[1], "_vs_", comparisons[2], "\n",
                     "Out of ", nrow(combined_data), " genes, ", nrow(de_genes_padj), " were below padj ", padjcutoff, "\n",
                     "Gene lists ordered by log2fchange have been generated.") )}

generate_DE_results(dds, c("Other Sarcoma", "CDS"), padjcutoff = 0.001)
## For the comparison: Other Sarcoma_vs_CDS

#Heat Map
variable_gene_heatmap <- function (dds, num_genes = 500) {
  vsd.obj <- vst(dds, blind = TRUE)
  brewer_palette <- "RdBu"
  # Ramp the color in order to get the scale.
  ramp <- colorRampPalette( RColorBrewer::brewer.pal(11, brewer_palette))
  mr <- ramp(256)[256:1]
  # get the stabilized counts from the vsd object
  stabilized_counts <- assay(vsd.obj)
  # calculate the variances by row(gene) to find out which genes are the most variable across the samples.
  row_variances <- rowVars(stabilized_counts)
  # get the top most variable genes
  top_variable_genes <- stabilized_counts[order(row_variances, decreasing=T)[1:num_genes],]
  # subtract out the means from each row, leaving the variances for each gene
  top_variable_genes <- top_variable_genes - rowMeans(top_variable_genes, na.rm=T)
  # replace the ensembl ids with the gene names
  annotation <- read.csv("GRCh38.p13_annotation.csv", header = T, stringsAsFactors = F)
  gene_names <- annotation$Gene.name[match(rownames(top_variable_genes), annotation$Gene.stable.ID)]
  rownames(top_variable_genes) <- gene_names
  # reconstruct colData without sizeFactors for heatmap labeling
  coldata <- as.data.frame(vsd.obj@colData)
  coldata$sizeFactor <- NULL
  coldata$replaceable <- NULL
  # draw heatmap using pheatmap
  pheatmap::pheatmap(top_variable_genes, color = mr, annotation_col = coldata, fontsize_col = 12, fontsize_row = 5, border_color = NA, fontsize = 5)
}

variable_gene_heatmap(dds, num_genes = 25)

#PCA Plot 
library(ggrepel)
plot_PCA = function (dds) {
  vsd.obj <- vst(dds, blind = TRUE)
  pcaData <- plotPCA(vsd.obj,  intgroup = c("condition"), returnData = T)
  percentVar <- round(100 * attr(pcaData, "percentVar"))
  ggplot(pcaData, aes(PC1, PC2, color=condition)) +
    geom_point(size=3) +
    labs(x = paste0("PC1: ",percentVar[1],"% variance"),
         y = paste0("PC2: ",percentVar[2],"% variance"),
         title = "PCA Plot") +
    ggrepel::geom_text_repel(aes(label = name), color = "black")
}
plot_PCA(dds)

# SHC3 Box Plot 
plot_counts <- function (dds, gene){
  annotation <- read.csv("GRCh38.p13_annotation.csv", header = TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
  normalized_data <- counts(dds, normalized = TRUE)
  condition <- dds@colData$condition
  # get the gene name from the ensembl id
  if (gene %in% annotation$Gene.name){ # check if a gene name is supplied
    ensembl_id <- annotation$Gene.stable.ID[which(annotation$Gene.name == gene)]
  } else if (gene %in% annotation$Gene.stable.ID){
    ensembl_id <- gene
  } else {
    stop("Gene not found. Check spelling.")
  }
  
  expression <- normalized_data[ensembl_id,]
  gene_name <- annotation$Gene.name[which(annotation$Gene.stable.ID == ensembl_id)]
  gene_tib <- tibble(condition = condition, expression = expression)
  ggplot(gene_tib, aes(x = condition, y = expression, col = condition))+
    geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA)+
    geom_jitter()+
    labs (title = paste0("Expression of ", gene_name, " - ", ensembl_id),
          x = "Group", y = paste("Normalized expression (DESeq2)"))+
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(size = 11), axis.text.y = element_text(size = 11))
}
plot_counts(dds, "SHC3")

# SHC4 Box Plot 
plot_counts(dds, "SHC4")

Summary

In this project, RNA sequencing data was used to compare the transcriptional profile of CDS cells to other sub-types of sarcoma. Prior to analysis, count tables were reorganized to include Ensembl gene name, gene symbol, cell line, and count. Next, a matrix was formed using the dcast function from the reshape2 package to create a table of counts for each cell line. To define genes that are unique to CDS, cell lines were characterized as either “CDS” or as “Other Sarcoma”, then DESeq2 was used for differential gene expression analysis.

Heat Map Until recently CDS was thought to be related to Ewing sarcoma due to having similar morphological features, however, recent clinical, molecular, and transcriptional comparisons of CDS and Ewing sarcoma show that CDS is a distinct entity with disparate mechanisms. To identify gene signatures unique to CDS, a heat map was generated based on variance. Based on the heat map generated, two adaptor proteins SHC3 and SHC4 are among the top 25 genes most uniquely expressed in CDS. Furthermore, this analysis identified DUSP6 (negative regulator of MAPK signaling) which has already been shown to play an important role in CDS tumorigenesis.

PCA Plot Considering CDS is now recognized as it’s own entity, it is important to validate that the human CDS cell lines used in this study are distict from the other sarcoma cell lines. Based off the PCA plot analysis, CDS cell lines clustered together and away from the other sarcoma cell lines. Furthermore, the PCA plot demonstrated that sarcoma cell lines of the same sarcoma type clustered together (sub-type labled not shown in PCA, but were grouped in code).

Box Plot Previous studies have shown adaptor proteins SHC3 and SHC4 play a role in other, non-sarcoma, cancer metastasis. To visualize the expression of these genes more closely, box plots were generated comparring SHC3/4 expression in CDS cells to other sarcoma cells. Based of this analysis, there is a clear difference in expression between CDS and non-CDS sarcoma cells.
